04896nam a22008535i 9781400852482DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2015    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008524827 a10.1515/97814008524822doi  a(DE-B1597)459875  a(OCoLC)895661669  a(OCoLC)984688247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA6931b.B3413 2017 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a873.012231 aBarchiesi, Alessandro, eauthor.10aHomeric Effects in Vergil's Narrative :bUpdated Edition /cAlessandro Barchiesi.  aUpdated edition with a New Foreword and New Afterword 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tINTRODUCTORY NOTE -- t1. The Death of Pallas Intertextuality and Transformation of the Epic Model -- t2. The Structure of Aeneid 10 -- t3. The Arms in the Sky -- t4. The Death of Turnus -- tAPPENDIX. The Lament of Juturna -- tAFTERWORD / rBarchiesi, Alessandro -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tSELECT INDEX -- tSELECT INDEX LOCORUM -- tINDEX OF MODERN AUTHORS  aThe study of Homeric imitations in Vergil has one of the longest traditions in Western culture, starting from the very moment the Aeneid was circulated. Homeric Effects in Vergil's Narrative is the first English translation of one of the most important and influential modern studies in this tradition. In this revised and expanded edition, Alessandro Barchiesi advances innovative approaches even as he recuperates significant earlier interpretations, from Servius to G. N. Knauer.Approaching Homeric allusions in the Aeneid as "narrative effects" rather than glimpses of the creative mind of the author at work, Homeric Effects in Vergil's Narrative demonstrates how these allusions generate hesitations and questions, as well as insights and guidance, and how they participate in the creation of narrative meaning. The book also examines how layers of competing interpretations in Homer are relevant to the Aeneid, revealing again the richness of the Homeric tradition as a component of meaning in the Aeneid. Finally, Homeric Effects in Vergil's Narrative goes beyond previous studies of the Aeneid by distinguishing between two forms of Homeric intertextuality: reusing a text as an individual model or as a generic matrix.For this edition, a new chapter has been added, and in a new afterword the author puts the book in the context of changes in the study of Latin literature and intertextuality.A masterful work of classical scholarship, Homeric Effects in Vergil's Narrative also has valuable insights for the wider study of imitation, allusion, intertextuality, epic, and literary theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aEpic poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 0aImitation in literature. 0aLatin poetryxGreek influences. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBarchiesi, Alessandro.1 aFox, Matt.1 aHardie, Philip.1 aMarchesi, Ilaria.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400852482zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400852482.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA